08329nam a22019935i 9780691189673DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911896737 a10.1515/97806911896732doi  a(DE-B1597)527260  a(OCoLC)1109956960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS147b.S66 2019eb 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a940.049242231 aSorkin, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJewish Emancipation :bA History across Five Centuries /cDavid Sorkin. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b17 b/w illus. 11 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction. Ambiguous and Interminable Emancipation -- tPart I. The Three Regions Emerge -- tPart II. The Two Legislative Models -- tPart III. The Three Regions in the Nineteenth Century -- tPart IV. The Fourth Region -- tPart V. Twentieth-Century Tribulations -- tConclusion. Ten Theses on Emancipation -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first comprehensive history of how Jews became citizens in the modern worldFor all their unquestionable importance, the Holocaust and the founding of the State of Israel now loom so large in modern Jewish history that we have mostly lost sight of the fact that they are only part of—and indeed reactions to—the central event of that history: emancipation. In this book, David Sorkin seeks to reorient Jewish history by offering the first comprehensive account in any language of the process by which Jews became citizens with civil and political rights in the modern world. Ranging from the mid-sixteenth century to the beginning of the twenty-first, the book tells the ongoing story of how Jews have gained, kept, lost, and recovered rights in Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, the United States, and Israel.Emancipation, Sorkin shows, was not a one-time or linear event that began with the Enlightenment or French Revolution and culminated with Jews' acquisition of rights in Central Europe in 1867–71 or Russia in 1917. Rather, emancipation was and is a complex, multidirectional, and ambiguous process characterized by deflections and reversals, defeats and successes, triumphs and tragedies. For example, American Jews mobilized twice for emancipation: in the nineteenth century for political rights and in the twentieth for lost civil rights. Similarly, Israel itself has struggled from the start to institute equality among its heterogeneous citizens.By telling the story of this foundational but neglected event, Jewish Emancipation reveals the lost contours of Jewish history over the past half millennium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJewsxEmancipationxHistory. 0aJews-Emancipation. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAbolitionism.  aAlgeria.  aAmerican Jewish Congress.  aAustria-Hungary.  aBlood libel.  aBourgeoisie.  aBureaucrat.  aCentral Europe.  aChief Rabbi.  aChristian state.  aCitizenship.  aCivil and political rights.  aCivil code.  aCivil defense.  aCivil service.  aCivil society.  aCongress Poland.  aConscription.  aCourt Jew.  aDecree.  aDeportation.  aDuchy of Warsaw.  aEastern Europe.  aEdict.  aEmigration.  aEmployment.  aEquality before the law.  aEurope.  aExclusion.  aFrench nationality law.  aGalicia (Spain).  aGerman Confederation.  aGreat power.  aHoly Roman Empire.  aImmigration.  aInfamous Decree.  aInstitution.  aIsraelites.  aJewish emancipation.  aJewish history.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aJurisdiction.  aJus sanguinis.  aJus soli.  aLawyer.  a